Overview

Here weve done an exploratory data analysis (EDA) of Data Analyst job market and used 2023 annual survey by Stack Overflow. For over a decade, Stack Overflow have been providing industry-leading insights into the developer community through its annual surveys. In the year 2023, over 90,000 developers participated in this survey. Analysts, IT leaders, reporters, and fellow developers rely on this report to stay informed about the ever-evolving developer landscape.

In our present study, weve filtered out Data Analysts responses from this years annual survey and tried to find different distributions based on education, age, coding experience, salary, country, working mode etc. Also, weve tried to use some statistical tests to verify some hypotesis.

Education Distribution

Most Data Analysts have attained a Bachelors degree (41%) with a third attaining a Masters degree (33%).

education_2023<-df_2023 %>% 
  drop_na(EdLevel) %>% 
  filter(DevType=="Data or business analyst") %>% 
  group_by(EdLevel) %>% 
  summarize(count=n()) %>% 
  mutate(percent = round(count / sum(count)*100, 0)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(percent))
education_2023[1,1] <- "Bachelor Degree"
education_2023[2,1] <- "Masters Degree"
education_2023[3,1]<- "Studied University/College"
education_2023[4,1] <- "Ph.D"
education_2023[5,1] <- "Associated Degree"
education_2023[6,1] <- "Secondary School"
education_2023$EdLevel <- factor(education_2023$EdLevel,                       levels = education_2023$EdLevel[order(education_2023$percent,            decreasing = FALSE)])
education_2023<-education_2023[-c(7:8),] # Remove last two insignificant levels
ggplot(data=education_2023, aes(x=EdLevel, y=percent)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity",fill="brown") +
  coord_flip()+
  geom_text(aes(label = paste(percent,"%")), vjust = 0.5, hjust=0.9, colour = "white") +
  labs(title="Data Analyst Distribution \nAcross Education Levels") +
  theme(axis.title.x = element_blank(),
  axis.title.y = element_blank())+
  theme(plot.title.position = 'plot', 
      plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

Skills in Demand

SQL (73%) is the most used programming language among Data Analyst, followed by Python (68%) and R (27%).

count_python=0
count_r=0
count_sql=0
#languages3=c("Python","R","SQL")
language_2023<-df_2023 %>% 
  drop_na(LanguageHaveWorkedWith) %>% 
  select(DevType,LanguageHaveWorkedWith) %>% 
  filter(DevType=="Data or business analyst")
col="LanguageHaveWorkedWith"
i<-0
for (row in 1:nrow(language_2023)){
  cell<-language_2023[row,col]
  if (is.na(cell)){
    next
  }
  #print(cell)
  #print(strsplit(as.character(cell),';',fixed=TRUE))
  for (value in strsplit(as.character(cell),';',fixed=TRUE)[[1]]){
    if (value=="Python"){
      count_python=count_python+1
      #print(count_python)
    }
    if(value=="R"){
      count_r=count_r+1
    }
    if(value=="SQL"){
      count_sql=count_sql+1
    }
    
  }
}
count_python<-count_python/nrow(language_2023)*100
count_r<-count_r/nrow(language_2023)*100
count_sql<-count_sql/nrow(language_2023)*100

programming<-c("Pyhon","R","SQL")
percent<-as.integer(c(count_python,count_r,count_sql))
programming_2023<-data.frame(programming,percent)
programming_2023
##   programming percent
## 1       Pyhon      68
## 2           R      27
## 3         SQL      73
ggplot(data=programming_2023, aes(x=programming, y=percent)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity",fill="brown") +
  coord_flip()+
  geom_text(aes(label = paste(percent,"%")), vjust = 0.5,hjust=1.0, colour = "white")+
  labs(title="Data Analyst Distribution \nBased on Programming Language Usage") +
  theme(axis.title.x = element_blank(),
  axis.title.y = element_blank())+
  theme(plot.title.position = 'plot', 
      plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

Salary Distribution across Industries, Regions and Experience Levels

In Canada, data analysts working in Finacial Institutes get the highest salary.

Salary in log scale has a linear relationship with work experience levels.

In Oil and Gas Industry, the salaries of Data Analysts have a wide range.

salary_2023<-df_2023 %>% 
  drop_na(Industry) %>% 
  filter(DevType=="Data or business analyst",Country=="Canada")
salary_2023$Industry[salary_2023$Industry=="Manufacturing, Transportation, or Supply Chain"]="Supply Chain"

salary_2023$Industry[salary_2023$Industry=="Information Services, IT, Software Development, or other Technology"]="IT"

t-test: Is there a difference in mean salary between USA and Canada?

According to the two sided t-test, there is significant difference in mean salary of Data Analyst between USA (Mean Salary: $ 116500 ) and Canada (Mean Salary: $ 75631 ).

df_2023 %>% 
  filter(Country %in% c("USA","Canada"),DevType=="Data or business analyst") %>% 
  t.test(ConvertedCompYearly~Country,data=.,
         alternative="two.sided")         
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  ConvertedCompYearly by Country
## t = -2.8292, df = 22.068, p-value = 0.009747
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group Canada and group USA is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -70820.32 -10915.96
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Canada    mean in group USA 
##             75631.89            116500.03
